A 10-day food record completed with photos of meals, snacks, and drinks was used to assess macronutrient intake during the sessions on the ground and inflight. Inflight, it was associated with systematically scanning the barcode of nonperishable food portion packages provided on the ISS. Notes about the consumed quantity were also provided by the astronauts. This allowed a quite precise estimation of both the quantity and quality of the food consumed inflight for all the subjects. On the ground, exploitable food records for at least 6 days were obtained in 7 subjects. Corresponding energy and macronutrient contents were obtained from food tables provided by NASA, ESA, JAXA, the Russian Space Agency, and CADMOS for inflight data and from CIQUAL food table63 for ground data. Food quotient or FQ was calculated using the equations of Black64:1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
